<TITLE> Gazipur agri univ closes indefinitely </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Gazipur, May 9 (bdnews24.com)  Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Agricultural University was indefinitely shut down on Sunday night after clashes between students and police. Male students were asked to leave the dormitories by 8:15pm to 9:15pm, while the females are to leave on Monday morning. Proctor Mohammed Jalal Uddin confirmed bdnews24.com: "The male students have already left the halls." bdnews24.com Gazipur correspondent reported that the university's authority expelled four students of the agriculture faculty on May 4 for failing to attain the minimum required CGPA of 2.5. Students of the faculty demonstrated from noon to 8pm on Thursday, boycotted classes, staged sit-in and submitted a memorandum to the vice-chancellor demanding withdrawal of the decision. On Sunday, the agitating students staged demonstration and a sit-in in front of the main entrance. Some 10 students fell sick due to the extreme heat. Two of them were admitted to Gazipur Sadar Hospital, resident doctor Mohammed Kamar Uddin told bdnews24.com. Jalal Uddin said that the demonstrators were further agitated by this incident and vandalised the bank building and wrecked the glasses of various faculty buildings and a bus at around 9pm. Police intervened to bring the situation under control. Students threw brickbats at them and fought a pitched battle with the police. The proctor said that a sufficient number of police led by a magistrate were deployed on the campus. Vice-chancellor Mohammed Abdul Mannan Akanda told bdnews24.com: "The steps were taken in accordance with the university's constitution and there is no scope to change the decision." According to the notice issued on Tuesday, the four had failed to attain the minimum GPA of 2.5 in three consecutive terms. They are second-year students Zubair Alam and Shahedur Rahman, and Laboni and Supti Chakma of the third year. bdnew
